IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA IS A PRIVATE, CATHOLIC INSTITUTION OFFERING COMPREHENSIVE UNDERGRADUATE AND GRADUATE PROGRAMS. OVER 1,000 STUDENTS ARE ENROLLED IN THE RESIDENTIAL UNDERGRADUATE COLLEGE AT THE WINONA CAMPUS, ESTABLISHED IN 1912. OVER THE COURSE OF A YEAR, MORE THAN 6,000 STUDENTS ARE ENROLLED IN THE SCHOOLS OF GRADUATE AND PROFESSIONAL PROGRAMS (SGPP), WHICH OFFERS CERTIFICATES, BACHELOR AND SPECIALIST PROGRAMS, MASTERS DEGREES AND DOCTORAL PROGRAMS. THE UNIVERSITY DELIVERS EDUCATION TO ITS ADULT LEARNERS THROUGH CAMPUSES IN MINNEAPOLIS; WINONA, NAIROBI, KENYA; AND ROCHESTER; AND AT NUMEROUS OTHER LOCATIONS IN MINNESOTA, WISCONSIN AND JAMAICA INCLUDING ONLINE. SAINT MARY'S IS ACCREDITED BY THE HIGHER LEARNING COMMISSION AND IS A MEMBER OF THE NORTH CENTRAL ASSOCIATION.
IRS990.MissionDesc: ENRICHED BY THE LASALLIAN CATHOLIC HERITAGE, SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA AWAKENS, NURTURES, AND EMPOWERS LEARNERS TO ETHICAL LIVES OF SERVICE AND LEADERSHIP.
IRS990.Desc: INSTRUCTION AND ACADEMIC SUPPORT:SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA HAS TWO PRIMARY ACADEMIC UNITS: THE COLLEGE AND THE SCHOOLS OF GRADUATE AND PROFESSIONAL PROGRAMS (SGPP). THE COLLEGE CONSISTS OF THE TRADITIONAL UNDERGRADUATE BACHELOR OF ARTS EXPERIENCE BASED ON THE WINONA CAMPUS. THE SGPP INCLUDES CONTINUING EDUCATION OFFERINGS, CERTIFICATE PROGRAMS, BACHELOR OF SCIENCE COMPLETION PROGRAMS, MASTER'S PROGRAMS, AN EDUCATION SPECIAL PROGRAM AND THREE DOCTORAL PROGRAMS. THE SGPP IS BASED ON BOTH THE TWIN CITIES AND WINONA CAMPUSES, WITH A CENTER IN ROCHESTER. ACROSS THE 12-MONTH 2019-2020 ACADEMIC YEAR THE COLLEGE ENROLLED 1,111 STUDENTS AND OFFERED 32,314 INSTRUCTIONAL ACTIVITY CREDIT HOURS. THE SGPP ENROLLED 5,855 STUDENTS ACROSS THE 2019-2020 ACADEMIC YEAR AND OFFERED 65,297 INSTRUCTIONAL ACTIVITY CREDIT HOURS. THE UNIVERSITY EXPECTS TO MAINTAIN ENROLLMENT AT SGPP IN 2020-2021, SERVING APPROXIMATELY 5,800 STUDENTS AND DELIVERING APPROXIMATELY 65,000 CREDIT HOURS. THE UNIVERSITY OFFERS 46 MAJORS WITH THE BACHELOR OF ARTS PROGRAM. THE UNIVERSITY OFFERS AN ADDITIONAL 58 PROGRAMS WITHIN THE SGPP.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: STUDENT SERVICES:IN 2019-2020, 358 TRADITIONAL UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS (ABOUT 30% OF THAT POPULATION) PARTICIPATED IN 17 NCAA DIVISION III SPORTS OFFERED AT SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY. PARTICIPATION IN INTRAMURAL ACTIVITIES ANNUALLY IS MORE THAN 40%. THE FINANCIAL AID OFFICE PROCESSED $68,884,699 IN LOANS, GRANTS, WORK STUDY AND SCHOLARSHIP FOR THE ENTIRE UNIVERSITY IN 2019-2020. 12% OF TRADITIONAL UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS WERE FORMALLY REGISTERED AS STUDENTS WITH DISABILITIES WITH THE INSTITUTION'S OFFICE OF DISABILITY SERVICES, THE MAJORITY OF WHICH UTILIZED SERVICES OFFERED BY THE UNIVERSITY. 128 INTERNATIONAL STUDENTS WERE ENROLLED AT THE UNIVERSITY IN 2019-2020. THIRTY STUDENTS PARTICIPATED IN THE FIRST GENERATION INITIATIVE PROGRAM, WHICH OFFERS SELECTED STUDENTS SCHOLARSHIPS TO ATTEND THE UNIVERSITY. THE STUDENTS ENGAGE IN SPECIAL SUPPORT ACTIVITIES WHICH INCLUDE STUDY HALLS, SPECIALIZED ADVISING AND SOCIAL ACTIVITIES WHICH PROMOTE RETENTION AND STUDENT SUCCESS.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: AUXILIARY SERVICES:SAINT MARYS' UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA OFFERS ITS WINONA UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS HOUSING, FOOD, AND OTHER SERVICES. LIVING ON CAMPUS MEANS BEING PART OF A CLOSE-KNIT COMMUNITY, AND CREATING FRIENDSHIPS AND CONNECTIONS THAT LAST A LIFETIME. TWELVE RESIDENCE HALLS ARE LOCATED ON OUR BEAUTIFUL WINONA CAMPUS, SURROUNDED BY 390 ACRES OF WOODED BLUFFS AND TRAILS. THESE HALLS OFFER STUDENTS A VARIETY OF TRADITIONAL, SUITE, AND APARTMENT-STYLE OPTIONS. SAINT MARYS' UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA OFFERS THREE CONVENIENT ON-CAMPUS DINING OPTIONS, EACH PROVIDING HEALTHY, HIGH QUALITY FOOD, BEVERAGES, AND SNACKS. THREE FACILITIES SERVE STUDENTS INCLUDING THE TONER STUDENT CENTER DINING HALL, CARDINAL CAFE, AND CARDINAL COFFEE. SEVERAL MEAL PLANS ARE TAILORED TO MEET EACH STUDENT'S NEEDS AND SCHEDULES. THE DINING SERVICES ARE ENVIRONMENTALLY CONSCIOUS AND HAVE TAKEN MANY STEPS TO REDUCE WASTE. STUDENTS CAN ALSO UTILIZE A NEW MARKET, WHICH CONTAINS A VARIETY OF CONVENIENT SNACKS AND BEVERAGES.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: LOBBYING ACTIVITIES: SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA IS A MEMBER OF MINNESOTA PRIVATE COLLEGE COUNCIL (MPCC), AN ORGANIZATION DESCRIBED IN SECTION 501(C)(4) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE. MPCC IS AN ASSOCIATION OF PRIVATE NONPROFIT INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER EDUCATION THAT SERVES A VARIETY OF ITS MEMBERS' SHARED NEEDS, INCLUDING, BUT NOT ONLY, NONPARTISAN AND NON-ELECTORAL ADVOCACY FOR PUBLIC POLICY THAT MEETS STUDENTS' NEEDS AND ADVANCES THE INTERESTS OF PRIVATE HIGHER EDUCATION. SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA PAID MEMBERSHIP DUES TO MPCC IN THE AMOUNT OF $153,098 DURING THE TAXABLE YEAR. MPCC HAS DIVIDED ITS EXPENSES FOR ITS TAXABLE YEAR ENDING JUNE 30, 2020 INTO TWO GROUPS. GROUP 1 CONSISTS OF THOSE EXPENSES THAT DID NOT IN ANY WAY SUPPORT ATTEMPTS TO INFLUENCE LEGISLATION WITHIN THE MEANING OF SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE ("LOBBYING"), AND GROUP 2 CONSISTS OF ALL OTHER EXPENSES. GROUP 2 INCLUDES MANY EXPENSES, SUCH AS PERSONNEL COSTS, THAT SUPPORTED BOTH LOBBYING AND NONLOBBYING ACTIVITIES. MPCC DID NOT ATTEMPT TO ALLOCATE THE GROUP 2 EXPENSES BETWEEN LOBBYING AND NON LOBBYING ACTIVITIES. MPCC HAS DETERMINED THAT THE AMOUNT OF THE GROUP 2 EXPENSES REPRESENTS 78.13% OF THE AMOUNT OF THE DUES THAT MPCC COLLECTED IN THE SAME TAXABLE YEAR. ASSUMING THAT ALL GROUP 2 EXPENSES WERE PAID FROM MEMBER DUES, AND ALLOCATING THOSE EXPENSES PRO RATA BASED ON THE DUES PAID BY EACH MEMBER, $119,618 OF SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA'S DUES WERE USED TO PAY GROUP 2 EXPENSES. THE AMOUNT OF LOBBYING EXPENSES PAID FROM SAINT MARY'S UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA'S DUES WAS SIGNIFICANTLY LESS THAN THAT AMOUNT.
THE ARTWORK AT THE UNIVERSITY INCLUDES PRINTS AND SCULPTURES THAT HELP TO SUPPORT OUR LASALLIAN MISSION AND ENHANCE THE SCHOLARLY ATMOSPHERE.
THE UNIVERSITY HOLDS AGENCY FUNDS AND SAVINGS FOR STUDENT GROUPS.
THE UNIVERSITY'S ENDOWMENT FUND EARNINGS ARE USED TO SUPPORT STUDENT SCHOLARSHIPS, STUDENT ASSISTANCE, AND SOME PROGRAM ENDOWMENTS.

THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE HAS DETERMINED THAT THE UNIVERSITY IS EXEMPT FROM FEDERAL INCOME TAX UNDER SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE. IT IS ALSO EXEMPT FROM STATE INCOME TAX. ACCORDINGLY, THE UNIVERSITY IS SUBJECT TO FEDERAL INCOME TAXES EXCEPT TO THE EXTENT IT DERIVES INCOME FROM CERTAIN ACTIVITIES NOT SUBSTANTIALLY RELATED TO ITS TAX-EXEMPT STATUS (UNRELATED BUSINESS ACTIVITIES). THE UNIVERSITY FOLLOWS THE ACCOUNTING STANDARDS FOR CONTINGENCIES IN EVALUATING UNCERTAIN TAX POSITIONS. THIS GUIDANCE PRESCRIBES RECOGNITION THRESHOLD PRINCIPLES FOR THE FINANCIAL STATEMENT RECOGNITION OF TAX POSITIONS TAKEN OR EXPECTED TO BE TAKEN ON A TAX RETURN THAT ARE NOT CERTAIN TO BE REALIZED. NO LIABILITY HAS BEEN RECOGNIZED BY THE UNIVERSITY FOR UNCERTAIN TAX POSITIONS AS OF MAY 31, 2020 AND 2019. THE UNIVERSITY'S TAX RETURNS ARE SUBJECT TO REVIEW AND EXAMINATION BY FEDERAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES.

THE UNIVERSITY INCLUDES A RACIALLY NONDISCRIMINATORY POLICY ON ALL APPLICATIONS, OUR WEBSITE, OUR UNDERGRADUATE AND GRADUATE CATALOGS, OUR FACT SHEET, OUR GRADUATE PROGRAM INFORMATION SHEETS AND OUR UNDERGRADUATE STUDENT RESOURCE AND DAILY PLANNER.

THE UNIVERSITY RECEIVES SUPPORT FROM THE STATE OF MINNESOTA AND FROM THE UNITED STATES GOVERNMENT IN CONNECTION WITH STUDENT AID PROGRAMS SUCH AS FEDERAL AND MINNESOTA COLLEGE WORK STUDY PROGRAMS, PELL GRANTS, SUPPLEMENTAL EDUCATIONAL OPPORTUNITY GRANTS AND PERKINS LOAN FUNDS. THE UNIVERSITY ALSO RECEIVES A GRANT FROM THE STATE OF MINNESOTA BASED ON MINNESOTA RESIDENTS ENROLLED AND VARIOUS OTHER FEDERAL AND STATE EDUCATIONAL AND RESEARCH GRANTS OR SUBSIDIES.
ACCRUAL METHOD
THE UNIVERSITY INVESTS IN PARTNERSHIPS THAT HOLD DIRECT OR INDIRECT INTERESTS IN FOREIGN CORPORATIONS. HOWEVER, THE UNIVERSITY DOES NOT MEET THE FILING REQUIREMENT OF FORM 5471 AS A RESULT.

THE UNIVERSITY INVESTS IN PARTNERSHIPS THAT HOLD DIRECT OR INDIRECT INTERESTS IN PASSIVE FOREIGN INVESTMENT COMPANIES. HOWEVER, THE PARTNERSHIPS HAVE FILED FORM 8621 ON THEIR PARTNERS' BEHALF, AND THEREFORE THE UNIVERSITY IS NOT REQUIRED TO FILE FORM 8621.
THE UNIVERSITY INVESTS IN PARTNERSHIPS THAT HOLD DIRECT OR INDIRECT INTERESTS IN FOREIGN PARTNERSHIPS. HOWEVER, THE UNIVERSITY DOES NOT MEET THE FILING REQUIREMENT OF FORM 8865 AS A RESULT.

THE UNIVERSITY DISTRIBUTES SCHOLARSHIPS BASED ON NEED AND MERIT. NEED BASED SCHOLARSHIPS ARE AWARDED BY THE FINANCIAL AID OFFICE USING THE INFORMATION FROM THE RESULTS OF THE FAFSA (FREE APPLICATION FOR FEDERAL STUDENT AID). MERIT BASED SCHOLARSHIPS ARE AWARDED BY THE ADMISSIONS OFFICE USING THE INFORMATION FROM THE STUDENT'S OFFICIAL HIGH SCHOOL TRANSCRIPTS AND THE RESULTS OF THE STANDARDIZED TEST (ACT, SAT, ETC.). FOR STUDENTS RECEIVING GRANTS AND SCHOLARSHIP FUNDS WITH RENEWAL CONDITIONS, FULFILLMENT OF THOSE CONDITIONS ARE VERIFIED BY THE FINANCIAL AID ADMINISTRATOR PRIOR TO THE AWARD BEING RENEWED (GPA, YEAR OF ATTENDANCE, ETC.)

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION A, LINE 1
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE HAS THE FULL POWERS OF THE BOARD TO TAKE SUCH ACTION AS MAY BE NECESSARY OR APPROPRIATE IN THE EVENT OF AN EMERGENCY OR OTHER EXIGENT CIRCUMSTANCES, AS DETERMINED BY EITHER THE PRESIDENT OR THE CHAIR. THE COMMITTEE CONSISTS OF THE CHAIR, THE VICE CHAIR, THE PRESIDENT, THE SECRETARY, THE TREASURER, THE CHAIR OF EACH OF THE STANDING COMMITTEES, THE IMMEDIATE PAST-CHAIR OF THE BOARD IF THAT PERSON IS STILL SERVING ON THE BOARD, AND THE PROVINCIAL OF THE MIDWEST DISTRICT OF THE BROTHERS OF THE CHRISTIAN SCHOOLS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION A, LINE 4
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION REVISED ITS ARTICLES OF INCORPORATION TO PROVDE THAT 6 MEMBERS OF THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES MUST BE BROTHERS OF THE CHRISTIAN SCHOOLS. THE ARTICLES PREVIOUSLY STATED THAT 25% OF THE BOARD WAS REQUIRED TO BE BROTHERS OF THE CHRISTIAN SCHOOLS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION A, LINE 6
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE BROTHERS OF THE CHRISTIAN SCHOOLS ARE CONSIDERED MEMBERS OF THE UNIVERSITY. THE BROTHERS OF THE CHRISTIAN SCHOOLS DO NOT HAVE ANY VOTING POWER.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION A, LINE 8B
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: EACH COMMITTEE REPORTS ITS ACTION TO THE GENERAL SESSION OF THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES. COMMITTEE ACTIONS ARE DOCUMENTED THROUGH THE MINUTES OF THE GENERAL SESSION.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 11B
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE AUDIT COMMITTEE OF THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES HAS THE RESPONSIBILITY OF REVIEWING AND APPROVING THE FORM 990. AFTER REVIEW BY THE AUDIT COMMITTEE, THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES RECEIVES A COPY OF THE PUBLIC INSPECTION COPY OF THE FORM 990.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 12C
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: IN JUNE OF EACH YEAR, TRUSTEES, OFFICE HOLDERS AND COMMITTEE MEMBERS DISCLOSE IN WRITING: (1) ALL CONTRACTS OR BUSINESS TRANSACTIONS BETWEEN THE UNIVERSITY AND THE TRUSTEE, OFFICE HOLDER OR COMMITTEE MEMBER; (2) ALL CONTRACTS OF BUSINESS TRANSACTIONS BETWEEN THE UNIVERSITY AND A FAMILY MEMBER; AND (3) ALL CONTRACTS OR BUSINESS TRANSACTIONS BETWEEN THE UNIVERSITY AND AN ORGANIZATION IN WHICH THE TRUSTEE, OFFICE HOLDER OR COMMITTEE MEMBER OR THEIR FAMILY MEMBER HAS A MATERIAL FINANCIAL INTEREST. ALL CONFLICTS OF INTEREST ARE REPORTED TO THE GENERAL COUNSEL AND THE CHAIR OF THE BOARD. THE GENERAL COUNSEL SHALL REVIEW THE REPORT AND THEN PRESENT A REPORT TO THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE WITH THE DETAILS OF THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST AND RECOMMENDATIONS. UPON RECEIPT OF THE REPORT FROM THE GENERAL COUNSEL, THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE SHALL MEET TO DETERMINE WHETHER A CONFLICT OF INTEREST EXISTS OR APPEARS TO EXIST. THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE SHALL RECORD A SUMMARY OF THE INTEREST, THE DETERMINATIONS MADE AND THE ACTIONS TAKEN BY THE COMMITTEE REGARDING THE POSSIBLE CONFLICT. THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE MAY TAKE ANY ACTION IT DEEMS APPROPRIATE INCLUDING: 1) FINDING THAT THE POTENTIAL CONFLICT OF INTEREST IS NOT DIRECT OR MATERIAL AND THAT THE UNIVERSITY'S INTERESTS ARE BEST SERVED BY THE TRUSTEE'S, OFFICE HOLDER'S OR COMMITTEE MEMBER'S PARTICIPATION; 2) RESTRICTING THE TRUSTEE, OFFICE HOLDER OR COMMITTEE MEMBER FROM ATTENDING ANY MEETING OR GATHERING AT ANY TIME AT WHICH THE MATTER IN QUESTION IS DISCUSSED; OR 3) UPON DETERMINING THAT THE CONTRACT OR BUSINESS TRANSACTION IS IN THE UNIVERSITY'S BEST INTEREST AND IS FAIR AND REASONABLE, APPROVE THE PROPOSED CONTRACT OR BUSINESS TRANSACTION.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 15A
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES IS RESPONSIBLE FOR REVIEWING, ASSESSING, AND APPROVING THE COMPENSATION FOR THE PRESIDENT ANNUALLY. EXTERNAL COUNSEL IS ENGAGED PERIODICALLY TO ASSIST WITH THE ASSESSMENT OF COMPENSATION. YAFFEE & COMPANY WAS ENGAGED IN 2017 TO COMPLETE A COMPENSATION STUDY FOR THE PRESIDENT. ADDITIONALLY, ACADEMIC SEARCH, AN EXECUTIVE SEARCH FIRM, COMPLETED A SALARY ANALYSIS AND PROPOSED COMPENSATION RECOMMENDATIONS AS PART OF ITS PRESIDENTIAL SEARCH PROCESS, COMPLETED IN MAY 2018. DATA FROM BOTH SOURCES WAS USED IN ESTABLISHING COMPENSATION FOR THE PRESIDENT. THE PRESIDENT, SUPPORTED BY THE AVP FOR HUMAN RESOURCES AND SENIOR VICE PRESIDENT FOR FINANCE AND OPERATIONS, IS RESPONSIBLE FOR REVIEWING, ASSESSING, AND APPROVING THE COMPENSATION OF ALL OTHER POSITIONS ANNUALLY. EXTERNAL COUNSEL IS ENGAGED PERIODICALLY TO ASSIST WITH THE ASSESSMENT OF EXECUTIVE-LEVEL COMPENSATION, DEFINED AS CABINET-LEVEL POSITIONS. YAFFEE & COMPANY WAS ENGAGED IN 2017 TO COMPLETE A COMPENSATION STUDY FOR CABINET-LEVEL POSITIONS. DATA FROM THE STUDY WAS USED IN ESTABLISHING COMPENSATION FOR CABINET POSITIONS. ADDITIONALLY, SALARY SURVEY DATA FROM CUPA-HR (COLLEGE UNIVERSITY PROFESSIONAL ASSOCIATION HUMAN RESOURCES), A NATIONAL DATA-BASE OF HIGHER EDUCATION SALARY INFORMATION, IS USED TO ASSESS AND ESTABLISH COMPENSATION FOR EMPLOYEES.

THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY IS AVAILABLE ON THE UNIVERSITY'S WEBSITE. FINANCIAL STATEMENTS ARE AVAILABLE UPON REQUEST AND THROUGH EMMA (ELECTRONIC MUNICIPAL MARKET ACCESS).
